pt:Chunk_33_20 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text "5.5 Data Preservation"^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_21 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text "Data preservation refers to the long-time storage of research data to enable the verification and reproduction of research and the re-use of data. Publishing and archiving data are the two most practical ways to preserve data after research."^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_22 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text """Digital research data needed for verification and reproduction (at least those underlying all types of academic publications, such as journal articles, reports, theses, etc.) have to be preserved in one of ITC‚Äôs approved data repositories or archive facilities for at least ten years after completion of the project (in accordance with The Netherlands Code of Conduct for Academic Practice).   
Preserved in a repository, research data can be published publicly, with restricted access, or embargoed. In accordance with the ITC‚Äôs Open Science Strategic Plan, the data should be published as open as possible and as closed as necessary, i.e., in case of legitimate reasons, such as ethical reasons, reasons concerning privacy protection and national security reasons, knowledge safety and export control, confidentiality, commercial interest, legal and contractual obligations reasons. However, the metadata must always be made available publicly.   
Digital research data that cannot be shared with third parties, including trusted data repositories, must be archived in UT‚Äôs archive facility.   
Research data underlying master's and PhD research projects must be preserved before graduation. Research data underlying other types of research projects must be preserved no later than one month after completion of the research project. Non-digital research data, wherever possible and appropriate, should be digitised. If the data is to be preserved in non-digital format, they should be stored securely in accordance with the respective department‚Äôs common practices.   
The primary author and co-authors of academic publications share the responsibility of controlling access and making any decision with respect to the data and, therefore, should all be acknowledged in the metadata of the archived or published datasets as contact persons.   
For research projects run by ITC researchers, access to the data with restricted access is controlled by the principal investigator. In situations where the original researchers are not available or no longer affiliated with ITC, access to the data is determined and granted by the department chair.   
Archived or published digital and non-digital research data require sufficient documentation to enable proper interpretation and re-use, as described in the section on Data Documentation."""^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_23 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text "For publishing research data, UT and ITC recommend two trusted research data repositories: DANS and 4TU.ResearchData."^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_24 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text "Trusted repositories are the repositories that have received a Core Trust Seal Certification, which warrants the reliability and durability of data repositories and, hence, the potential for storing data over a long period of time."^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_25 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_7 ;
    ns1:text """For archiving research data, UT has a certified facility for long-term research data archiving known as AREDA. It is required to contact the Faculty Data Steward before archiving data in AREDA.   
For archiving research data from master research projects, ITC has a separate archive facility."""^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_26 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_9 ;
    ns1:text """5.6 Data Registration in PURE  

The registration of research output in Pure, including research data, is essential for consolidating information from various sources at one single platform in order to offer a comprehensive overview of ITC research activities and their impact.  

All archived or published digital and non-digital data must be registered in Pure (UT Research Information), where their metadata information is recorded to increase visibility.  

Step-by-step guidelines, including a Demo and more guidance on registering research output, are available on the UT Research Information Website"""^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_27 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text "5.7 Personal, Confidential, and Classified Research Data Management"^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_28 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text "Warranting the protection of confidential data, privacy, and the rights of research subjects is paramount in all research activities conducted within ITC. This section outlines key principles, ctices, and compliance measures related to the handling of personal and confidential data in research:"^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_33_29 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_16 ;
    ns1:text "All research activities involving personal data must adhere to the principles and requirements outlined in the GDPR;"^^xsd:string .

