pt:Chunk_34_4 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text """Brief context  

The policy proposed in this document aims to be in line with the various initiatives that have been published by the European Commission, namely the Recommendation of 2012 on access to and preservation of scientific information and its update in 2018.  

This document also took into account the Horizon 2020 guidelines on rules of open access to scientific publications; Regulation (EU) 2021/695 of the European Parliament and of the Council establishing Horizon Europe ‚Äì the Framework Programme for Research and Innovation, laying down its rules for participation and dissemination, and Council Decision (EU) 2021/764 establishing the specific programme implementing Horizon Europe ‚Äì the Framework Programme for Research and Innovation.  

It also takes into consideration important developments at a European level related to Open Science and Open Access, such as the EU Council Conclusions of 2016 on the transition towards an Open Science system, the ‚ÄòPlan S‚Äô and ‚ÄòcOAlition S‚Äô, the developments of the European Open Science Cloud (EOSC) and in particular the Strategic Research and Innovation Agenda, the action lines of the EU Open Science Policy, the Resolution on ‚ÄúA new ERA for Research and Innovation‚Äù and EU Directive 2019 on open data and the reuse of public-sector information and the Report "Towards a 2030 Vision on the Future of Universities in Europe‚Äù.  

Finally, it considers other relevant reports such as: ‚ÄúPerspectives on the new European Research Area from the university sector‚Äù, ‚ÄúUniversities without walls: A vision for 2030‚Äù of the  European University Association, ‚ÄúLooking to the Future: the Guild‚Äôs Vision for Europe‚Äôs Universities‚Äù of The Guild of European Research-Intensive Universities, and Science Europe‚Äôs practical guide ‚ÄúInternational Alignment of Research Data Management.‚Äù"""^^xsd:string .

pt:Chunk_34_5 a ns1:chunk ;
    pt:describes pt:Topic_-1 ;
    ns1:text """Benefits and advantages of Open Science  

Open Science is a scientific activity conducted in an open, collaborative and transparent manner, in all fields of knowledge, from the basic sciences to the social sciences and humanities.2,3 It has the potential to increase the quality and efficiency of research and fast-track the advancement of knowledge and innovation through the sharing of results, making them more reusable and improving their reproducibility. It is based on the following principles:  

transparency in practices, methodology, observation and data collection;   
the provision, public access, reuse and replicability of research results and methods;   
transparency in scientific communication;   
the use of web-based tools to facilitate scientific collaboration."""^^xsd:string .

